The AST-as-pipeline-IR pattern is easiest to see in a visitor rewrite. In pseudocode, a plugin can replace one syntactic form with another:

```javascript
export default function plugin({ types }) {
  return {
    visitor: {
      BinaryExpression(path) {
        if (path.node.operator === "**") {
          path.replaceWith(
            types.callExpression(types.identifier("pow"), [
              path.node.left,
              path.node.right
            ])
          );
        }
      }
    }
  };
}
```

The generic pattern is powerful when a language wants third-party syntactic transforms: every pass speaks one stable tree API, and plugins compose by mutating or replacing nodes. The cost is that the API freezes source-shaped structure; deeper optimizations usually want a separate IR with explicit control flow, values, and effects.
